      Flexible Sulfide Electrolyte Thin Membrane with Ultrahigh Ionic Conductivity for All-Solid-State Lithium Batteries

      Abstract

      Click to copy section linkSection link copied!

      All-solid-state lithium batteries (ASSLBs) employing Li-metal anode, sulfide solid electrolyte (SE) can deliver high energy density with high safety. The thick SE separator and its low ionic conductivity are two major challenges. Herein, a 30 μm sulfide SE membrane with ultrahigh room temperature conductivity of 8.4 mS cm–1 is realized by mechanized manufacturing technologies using highly conductive Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 SE powder. Moreover, a 400 nm magnetron sputtered Al2O3 interlayer is introduced into the SE/Li interface to improve the anodic stability, which suppresses the short circuit in Li/Li symmetric cells. Combining these merits, ASSLBs with LiNi0.5Co0.2Mn0.3O2 as the cathode exhibit a stable cyclic performance, delivering a discharge specific capacity of 135.3 mAh g–1 (1.4 mAh cm–2) with a retention of 80.2% after 150 cycles and an average Coulombic efficiency over 99.5%. The high ionic conductivity SE membrane and interface design principle show promising feasible strategies for practical high performance ASSLBs.

      In recent decades, the goal toward a low-carbon economy through electrification of automobiles for widespread adoption has greatly incentivized the endeavor of high specific energy lithium (Li)-ion batteries. Strategies ranging from novel materials investigation to advanced structural design development span the efforts. (1,2) However, the flammable, reactive organic electrolytes in conventional Li ion batteries incur severe safety issues, and the use of a high specific energy Li-metal anode (3860 mAh g–1) tends to aggravate risks, since anodic interface reactions and dendrite-like growth of Li degrade cell performance and short-circuit batteries. (3,4)

      All-solid-state Li batteries (ASSLBs) coupling sulfide solid electrolytes (SEs) and Li-metal anode are promising alternative strategies to realize nonflammability and promising high energy density. (5−7) Some SEs, such as Li5.5PS4.5Cl1.5 (9.4 ± 0.1 mS cm–1), (8) Li10GeP2S12 (12 mS cm–1), (9) and Li9.54Si1.74P1.44S11.7Cl0.3 (25 mS cm–1), (10) possess superior Li ion conductivity than liquid electrolyte, enabling high power density of cells. However, there are wide gaps between reality and ideal. Most of the sulfide ASSLBs can only achieve the one-tenth gravimetric specific energy of Li ion batteries, which is largely caused by the relatively thick anode layer and SE separator. (11) Recently, Lee et al. demonstrated significant progress on ASSLBs (900 Wh L–1) enabled by a 10 μm thick composite anode and a 30 μm thick SE membrane, highlighting the indispensability of thin SE layers. (12) To fabricate thin sulfide SEs, various approaches have been employed, including slurry processable SEs, (13,14) solution-processable SE with scaffolds, (15) and sulfide–polymer hybrid electrolytes, (16) whereas traditional wet technology has its limitations such as solvent toxicity and reactivity between SE and solvents, leading to inferior ionic conductivity. (17) To address solvent issues, Hippauf et al. reported a heuristic solvent-free dry-film process whereby they prepared a 150 μm thick SE film with the ionic conductivity of 2.7 mS cm–1 using fibrous polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) binder and Li6PS5Cl. (18) However, the preparation process, the thickness, the conductivity, and the instability to the Li-metal anode of SE films still need to be further improved.

      In this work, we achieve a much thinner flexible sulfide SE membrane (∼30 μm) with ultrahigh conductivity (8.4 mS cm–1 at 25 °C) enabled by mechanized manufacture technologies using highly conductive Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 sulfide SE powder (10.8 mS cm–1 at 25 °C). A typical preparation procedure of the SE membrane is schematically shown in Figure 1. With the SE powder (99.8 wt %) and PTFE powder (0.2 wt %) as the starting materials, a ball-milling process is adopted to mix the ingredients and shear the PTFE fiber, which forms a matrix to support SE particles. After being hot calendered at 80 °C, the homogeneous mixture can be mechanically formed to thin membranes with preset thickness. The obtained composite membrane, as illustrated in the magnified scheme on the right of Figure 1a, is a 3D continuous PTFE network wrapped with SE particles. To achieve a high ionic conductivity SE membrane, the argyrodite SE, Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6, was synthesized by introducing chlorine ion (Cl–) to tailor the S/Cl disorder in the lattice structure. The synthesis parameters for Li7–xPS6–xClx (x = 1.4, 1.5, 1.6, 1.7) are systematically investigated, and the Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 powder delivers the highest ionic conductivity of up to 10.8 mS cm–1 (Figure S1) with a low electronic conductivity of 4.0 × 10–8 S cm–1 at 25 °C (Figure S2). All Li7–xPS6–xClx samples match well with the standard argyrodite phase of cubic Li7PS6 (PDF 34-0688) with a space group of F4̅3m (Figure S3a), and all the diffraction peaks in the range of 52–54° continue to shift to the higher angles with increasing LiCl doping contents until x = 1.6 in Li7–xPS6–xClx (Figure S3b). This indicates shrinkage of crystal lattice parameters and the increased Li occupancy at 24g sites, which contributes to shortening the intercage jump distances and thus promoting the long-range ion conduction. (19,20)Figure 1b shows the hot calendering process, which can be run continuously and scaled up. After being peeled off, the SE membrane exhibits a typical faint yellow color due to a high fraction of Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 powder. It is free-standing, flexible, and continuous with a controlled thickness of 30 μm (Figure 1c and d). Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) observation further confirms its thickness (Figure 1e) and the highly bonded small particles that are netted by polymer fibers (Figure 1f). Energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX) mapping of the elements sulfur and fluorine, derived from Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 and PTFE, proves the uniform distribution of sulfide electrolyte throughout the polymer network (Figure 1g and h).

      Figure 2a shows a height profile of a prepared SE membrane by atomic force microscopy (AFM) testing, from which an average surface roughness of 121 nm can be analyzed, indicating that the hot calendering process can realize a thin and smooth membrane simultaneously. Actually, it is essential to achieve an even SE surface because the insufficient contact of SE and electrodes is the origin of high interfacial impedances and high current focusing. (21)Figure 2b shows the variable-temperature ionic conductivities of SE powder as well as the membrane, and the Nyquist plots are shown in Figure S4. Although PTFE is a nonconductive polymer, it occupies a minimal volume in the composite, maximizing the electrolyte phase content, which guarantees the Li+ conductive component in the membrane. Thus, the SE membrane exhibits an ionic conductivity of 8.4 mS cm–1 with a low area specific resistance of 0.35 Ω cm2 at 25 °C, which is close to the 10.8 mS cm–1 of the SE powder and greatly exceeds that of the state-of-the-art SE membranes reported in the literature (Figure 2c; the detailed parameters are shown in Table S1). (12,13,15,18,22−27) In addition, the high ionic conductivity of the SE membrane can be attributed to the dry-film process avoiding the solvent effect. The fast, mechanized, and solvent-free preparation minimized the damage to the SE material surface structure, which is further characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD). As shown in Figure S5, the Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 SE powder and membrane match well with the standard argyrodite phase. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS, Figure 2d) survey of the SE membrane for the F 1s signal at 690 cm–1, and the C 1s signal between 291 and 292 cm–1 can be deconvoluted to −CF, −CF3, and −CF2 bonds in PTFE chains, respectively. (28) The other almost identical peaks in both SE powder and the membrane indicate the addition of PTFE does not change the SE surface property (Figure S6), highlighting the nondestructive preparation process.

      The stability and compatibility with the Li-metal anode are another challenge to overcome for the application of SEs. Generally, some sulfide SEs are thermodynamically unstable with Li-metal; an ion–electron mixed conducting interphase would spontaneously form upon contact, resulting in undesired growth of the interphase and gradually leading to high polarization and cell failure. (29) Under the phase equilibrium, interphases of Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 and Li-metal are LiCl, Li2S, and Li3P, (30) constructing a kinetically self-limiting interface with the formation of an almost exclusively ion conducting metastable solid electrolyte interface (SEI). However, PTFE is known to readily accept electrons and convert to carbine-type carbon through defluorination by the chemical reaction with alkali metals or electrochemical reduction in an anodic environment. The carbine-type carbon is easily transformed to electrically conducting sp2 carbon and forms an undesirable mixed conducting interphase, collapsing the metastable state of SEI as well as increasing the electronic conductivity of SE. (31) To alleviate this issue, a stable artificial interlayer should be introduced to the interface between the SE membrane and the Li-metal anode. The aluminum oxide (Al2O3) passivation layer can prevent side reactions between Li and electrolytes effectively and tends to form a thermodynamically stable phase of the Li2O–Al2O3 layer with ionic conductivity (6 × 10–8 S cm–1 at 25 °C) due to its low binding energy with Li, which would greatly negate the interface impedance and heighten the adhesion to interfaces. (32−34) It is suggested that the lithiation of Al2O3 proceeds until it reaches the thermodynamically stable phase of Li3.4Al2O3; then, extra Li ions transport to the electrode through the LixAl2O3 coating layer. (33) In this case, an Al2O3 coating layer with a thickness of 400 nm was deposited on the Li surface by radiofrequency magnetron sputtering (Figure 3a). The elemental mapping image clearly indicates the Al distribution at the surface of the Li-metal (Figure 3b), and the diffusion behavior of Al and O across the Al2O3/Li interface can be identified in Figure S7, indicating the integration of interfacial phases (selected area with dashed line in Figure 3c). The interface stability was evaluated by plating/striping Li-metal in symmetric cells. Figure 3d shows the time-dependent voltage profile of cells under a current density of 0.1 mA cm–2 and 0.1 mAh cm–2 at 60 °C. The cell of Li/Al2O3/membrane/Al2O3/Li exhibits a voltage of ±7 mV in the beginning and then remains relatively stable at about ±9 mV for 180 h. After that, the voltage gradually increases to ±12 mV after 400 h of cycling without any internal short circuits. In contrast, although the symmetric Li/membrane/Li cell exhibits an initial voltage of ±5 mV, it short-circuits within 12 h (Figure 3e). The remarkable difference in cycle life strongly supports the effectiveness of the Al2O3 interlayer in short circuit suppression.

      To get a further understanding of the interface behaviors, the interphases with or without the Al2O3 interlayer were characterized after cell cycling. Figure 3f shows the XPS spectrum of the interphases, where the peaks in the F1s spectra at 685 and 690 eV are associated with LiF and the −CF bond, respectively. For Li/membrane/Li cells without an Al2O3 interlayer, LiF was generated, as proved by the presence of F1s spectra at 685 eV. However, for Li/Al2O3/membrane/Al2O3/Li cells, an intense −CF bond signal can be identified at 690 eV, suggesting that the side reaction is effectually suppressed. Raman spectroscopy (Figure 3g) further confirms the positive effects of the Al2O3. The bands at 1330 cm–1 (D band) and 1580 cm–1 (G band) indicate a significant amount of carbon formation in the interface without an interlayer. (35) By contrast, the interphase of the Li/Al2O3/membrane only displays the signals from PTFE, underscoring the significant role of the Al2O3 interlayer on side reaction suppression. Although the carbon at the SE/Li interface is not sufficient to cause a serious short circuit, PTFE is highly reactive with Li-metal, thus forming an interior continuous electron conductive network in the SE membrane. As shown in Figure 3h, the carbon-containing mixed conducting phase at the SE/Li interface cannot lead to the drop of Li chemical potential (μLi) across the SE, since sufficient electronic conduction offers high electron electrochemical potential. (36) As a result, the inner PTFE network wrapping with SE particles is still exposed to the high μLi of Li-metal, leading to the continued reduction reaction between PTFE and Li. Nevertheless, it is believed that during direct contact and electrochemical cycling, Al2O3 can be lithiated and converted to an exclusive Li+ conductor which not only separates Li and SE but blocks electrons, resulting in the low μLi and stable interface. (33)

      The electrochemical performances of the SE membrane in ASSLBs were further evaluated, where the LiNi0.5Co0.2Mn0.3O2 (NCM)/Li system was employed. The flexible and free-standing membrane can be easily used in ASSLBs by the simple isostatic cold pressing method. The cross-sectional electron back scattered diffraction (EBSD) image clearly reveals the stacked integrated structure of the ASSLB, and the thickness of the compressed SE membrane is about 30 μm (Figure 4a). EDX element mapping (Figure 4b–d) shows that nickel (Ni) is uniformly distributed on the cathode, while sulfur (S) and phosphorus (P) are mainly distributed on the SE, highlighting the compact integration of layers. Figure 4e shows the charge–discharge curves of NCM-Li ASSLBs tested at 0.05 C under 60 °C, and the mass loading of the active material NCM is 11.6 mg cm–2. It is noted that the initial discharge capacity is 100.1 mAh g–1 with a Coulombic efficiency of 67.1%, which may be attributed to the possible disconnection at the electrode–current collector interface or temporary discharge polarization caused by SEI formation. (37) After that, the discharge capacity gradually increases, delivering a reversible discharge capacity up to 135.3 mAh g–1, corresponding to 1.4 mAh cm–2 at the 20th cycle. After 150 cycles, it still remains 108.5 mAh g–1 (1.12 mAh cm–2) with a capacity retention of 80.2% (Figure 4f). It is noteworthy that over 99.5% of the average Coulombic efficiency of the ASSLB is delivered during the charge/discharge cycling except the first cycle (Figure S8), indicating highly reversible electrode reactions. To understand the probable reason for capacity fade, electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) measurement on the ASSLB was conducted. Figure S9 shows the Nyquist plots of the ASSLB after the first and 150th cycle. The semicircles observed at the medium frequency (100 Hz) can be regarded as the resistances in the positive electrode layer including the interfacial resistance of NCM/LPSC and the charge transfer impedance of the cathode layer. (38) It increases by about 1.4 times at the 150th cycle (128.4 Ω vs 181.7 Ω), suggesting that the stability and compatibility of the cathodic interface need to be improved.

      In summary, we designed and realized a high-performance SE membrane composed of an interconnected PTFE polymer net and a Li5.4PS4.4Cl1.6 sulfide electrolyte. The obtained composite membrane possesses a much higher ionic conductivity of 8.4 mS cm–1 with a thin thickness of 30 μm. The fabrication methodology with high mechanization and flexibility of the membrane ensures running continuously and scale up. It is noteworthy that an Al2O3 interlayer between the SE membrane and Li has been demonstrated to achieve physical separation and lead to the decrease of μLi, thus alleviating the short circuit problems. As a consequence, full cells with NCM as the cathodes were evaluated and exhibited stable cycling stability, delivering a discharge specific capacity of 135.3 mAh g–1 (1.4 mAh cm–2) with a capacity retention of 80.2% for 150 cycles under an average Coulombic efficiency over 99.5%. The presented SE membrane not only proves a promising design principle on thin and highly Li-ion conductive SEs but also paves the way for the next-generation high-energy ASSLBs.

        Thermally modulated lithium iron phosphate batteries for mass-market electric vehicles
        Yang, Xiao-Guang; Liu, Teng; Wang, Chao-Yang
        Nature Energy (2021), 6 (2), 176-185CODEN: NEANFD; ISSN:2058-7546. (Nature Research)
        The pursuit of energy d. has driven elec. vehicle (EV) batteries from using lithium iron phosphate (LFP) cathodes in early days to ternary layered oxides increasingly rich in nickel; however, it is impossible to forgo the LFP battery due to its unsurpassed safety, as well as its low cost and cobalt-free nature. Here we demonstrate a thermally modulated LFP battery to offer an adequate cruise range per charge that is extendable by 10 min recharge in all climates, essentially guaranteeing EVs that are free of range anxiety. Such a thermally modulated LFP battery designed to operate at a working temp. around 60°C in any ambient condition promises to be a well-rounded powertrain for mass-market EVs.         How do Li atoms pass through the Al2O3 coating layer during lithiation in Li-ion batteries?
        Jung, Sung Chul; Han, Young-Kyu
        Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters (2013), 4 (16), 2681-2685CODEN: JPCLCD; ISSN:1948-7185. (American Chemical Society)
        We studied the lithiation of Al2O3 and found the energetically most favorable compn. of Li3.4Al2O3 using ab initio mol. dynamics simulations. The calcd.         Randau, Simon; Walther, Felix; Neumann, Anton; Schneider, Yannik; Negi, Rajendra S.; Mogwitz, Boris; Sann, Joachim; Becker-Steinberger, Katharina; Danner, Timo; Hein, Simon; Latz, Arnulf; Richter, Felix H.; Janek, Juergen

        All-solid-state lithium-ion batteries have the potential to become an important class of next-generation electrochem. energy storage devices.           Yang, X.-G.; Liu, T.; Wang, C.-Y. Thermally modulated lithium iron phosphate batteries for mass-market electric vehicles. Nat. Energy 2021, 6 (2), 176– 185,  DOI: 10.1038/s41560-020-00757-7
          1
          Thermally modulated lithium iron phosphate batteries for mass-market electric vehicles
          Yang, Xiao-Guang; Liu, Teng; Wang, Chao-Yang
          Nature Energy (2021), 6 (2), 176-185CODEN: NEANFD; ISSN:2058-7546. (Nature Research)
          The pursuit of energy d. has driven elec. vehicle (EV) batteries from using lithium iron phosphate (LFP) cathodes in early days to ternary layered oxides increasingly rich in nickel; however, it is impossible to forgo the LFP battery due to its unsurpassed safety, as well as its low cost and cobalt-free nature. Here we demonstrate a thermally modulated LFP battery to offer an adequate cruise range per charge that is extendable by 10 min recharge in all climates, essentially guaranteeing EVs that are free of range anxiety. Such a thermally modulated LFP battery designed to operate at a working temp. around 60°C in any ambient condition promises to be a well-rounded powertrain for mass-market EVs. Furthermore, we reveal that the limited working time at the high temp. presents an opportunity to use graphite of low surface areas, thereby prospectively prolonging the EV lifespan to greater than two million miles.

          How do Li atoms pass through the Al2O3 coating layer during lithiation in Li-ion batteries?
          Jung, Sung Chul; Han, Young-Kyu
          Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters (2013), 4 (16), 2681-2685CODEN: JPCLCD; ISSN:1948-7185. (American Chemical Society)
          We studied the lithiation of Al2O3 and found the energetically most favorable compn. of Li3.4Al2O3 using ab initio mol. dynamics simulations. The calcd. Li/Al ratio and corresponding vol. expansion ratio agree well with reported exptl. observations. The Al atoms accept electrons from the incoming Li atoms during lithiation, leading to the formation of various Al structures, i.e., isolated atoms, dimers, trimers, and ring- and chain-type clusters. The Li atoms in the optimal concn. diffuse faster by four (five) orders of magnitude than the Al (O) atoms, and they also diffuse faster by four orders of magnitude than the Li atoms in a dil. Li concn. We suggest that in Li-ion batteries the lithiation of the Al2O3 coating layer proceeds until a thermodynamically stable phase is reached; then, extra Li atoms overflow into the electrode by passing through the coating layer.

          Next-Generation Lithium Metal Anode Engineering via Atomic Layer Deposition
          Kozen, Alexander C.; Lin, Chuan-Fu; Pearse, Alexander J.; Schroeder, Marshall A.; Han, Xiaogang; Hu, Liangbing; Lee, Sang-Bok; Rubloff, Gary W.; Noked, Malachi
          ACS Nano (2015), 9 (6), 5884-5892CODEN: ANCAC3; ISSN:1936-0851. (American Chemical Society)
          Li metal is considered to be the most promising anode for next-generation batteries due to its high energy d. of 3840 mAh g-1. However, the extreme reactivity of the Li surface can induce parasitic reactions with solvents, contamination, and shuttled active species in the electrolyte, reducing the performance of batteries employing Li metal anodes. One promising soln. to this issue is application of thin chem. protection layers to the Li metal surface. Using a custom-made ultrahigh vacuum integrated deposition and characterization system, the authors demonstrate at. layer deposition (ALD) of protection layers directly on Li metal with exquisite thickness control. The authors demonstrate as a proof-of-concept that a 14. nm thick ALD Al2O3 layer can protect the Li surface from corrosion due to atm., S, and electrolyte exposure. Using Li-S battery cells as a test system, the authors demonstrate an improved capacity retention using ALD-protected anodes over cells assembled with bare Li metal anodes for up to 100 cycles.

          Yu, Y.; Huang, G.; Wang, J.-Z.; Li, K.; Ma, J.-L.; Zhang, X.-B. In Situ Designing a Gradient Li+ Capture and Quasi-Spontaneous Diffusion Anode Protection Layer toward Long-Life Li–O2 Batteries. Adv. Mater. 2020, 32 (38), 2004157,  DOI: 10.1002/adma.202004157

          In Situ Designing a Gradient Li+ Capture and Quasi-Spontaneous Diffusion Anode Protection Layer toward Long-Life Li-O2 Batteries
          Yu, Yue; Huang, Gang; Wang, Jia-Zhi; Li, Kai; Ma, Jin-Ling; Zhang, Xin-Bo
          Advanced Materials (Weinheim, Germany) (2020), 32 (38), 2004157CODEN: ADVMEW; ISSN:0935-9648. (Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA)
          Lithium metal is the only anode material that can enable the Li-O2 battery to realize its high theor. energy d. (≈3500 Wh kg-1). However, the inherent uncontrolled dendrite growth and serious corrosion limitations of lithium metal anodes make it experience fast degrdn. and impede the practical application of Li-O2 batteries. Herein, a multifunctional complementary LiF/F-doped carbon gradient protection layer on a lithium metal anode by one-step in situ reaction of molten Li with poly(tetrafluoroethylene) (PTFE) is developed. The abundant strong polar C-F bonds in the upper carbon can not only act as Li+ capture site to pre-uniform Li+ flux but also regulate the electron configuration of LiF to make Li+ quasi-spontaneously diffuse from carbon to LiF surface, avoiding the strong Li+-adhesion-induced Li aggregation. For LiF, it can behave as fast Li+ conductor and homogenize the nucleation sites on lithium, as well as ensure firm connection with lithium. As a result, this well-designed protection layer endows the Li metal anode with dendrite-free plating/stripping and anticorrosion behavior both in ether-based and carbonate ester-based electrolytes. Even applied protected Li anodes in Li-O2 batteries, its superiority can still be maintained, making the cell achieve stable cycling performance (180 cycles).

          Mobile Ions in Composite Solids
          Zou, Zheyi; Li, Yajie; Lu, Ziheng; Wang, Da; Cui, Yanhua; Guo, Bingkun; Li, Yuanji; Liang, Xinmiao; Feng, Jiwen; Li, Hong; Nan, Ce-Wen; Armand, Michel; Chen, Liquan; Xu, Kang; Shi, Siqi
          Chemical Reviews (Washington, DC, United States) (2020), 120 (9), 4169-4221CODEN: CHREAY; ISSN:0009-2665. (American Chemical Society)
          A review. Fast ion conduction in solid-state matrixes constitutes the foundation for a wide spectrum of electrochem. systems that use solid electrolytes (SEs), examples of which include solid-state batteries (SSBs), solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs), and diversified gas sensors. Mixing different solid conductors to form composite solid electrolytes (CSEs) introduces unique opportunities for SEs to possess exceptional overall performance far superior to their individual parental solids, thanks to the abundant chem. and physics at the new interfaces thus created. In this review, a comprehensive and in-depth examn. is provided of the development and understanding of CSEs for SSBs, with special focus on their physiochem. properties and mechanisms of ion transport therein. The origin of the enhanced ionic cond. in CSEs relative to their single-phase parents is discussed in the context of defect chem. and interfacial reactions. The models/theories for ion movement in diversified composites are critically reviewed to interrogate a general strategy to the design of novel CSEs, while properties such as mech. strength and electrochem. stability are discussed in view of their perspective applications in lithium metal batteries and beyond. As an integral component of understanding how ions interact with their composite environments, characterization techniques to probe the ion transport kinetics across different temporal and spatial time scales are also summarized.

          On the Additive Microstructure in Composite Cathodes and Alumina-Coated Carbon Microwires for Improved All-Solid-State Batteries
          Randau, Simon; Walther, Felix; Neumann, Anton; Schneider, Yannik; Negi, Rajendra S.; Mogwitz, Boris; Sann, Joachim; Becker-Steinberger, Katharina; Danner, Timo; Hein, Simon; Latz, Arnulf; Richter, Felix H.; Janek, Juergen
          Chemistry of Materials (2021), 33 (4), 1380-1393CODEN: CMATEX; ISSN:0897-4756. (American Chemical Society)
          All-solid-state batteries promise to enable lithium metal anodes and outperform state-of-the-art lithium-ion battery technol. To achieve high battery capacity, utilization of the active material in the cathode must be maximized. Carbon-based conductive additives are known to improve the capacity and rate performance of electrode composites. However, their influence on cathode composites in all-solid-state batteries is yet not fully understood. Here, we study the influence of several carbon additives with different morphologies and surface areas on the performance of an all-solid-state battery cell Li|β-Li3PS4|Li(Ni0.6Co0.2Mn0.2)O2/β-Li3PS4/carbon. Cycling tests and microstructure-resolved simulations show that higher utilization of the cathode active material can be achieved using fiber-shaped vapor-grown carbon additives, whereas particle-shaped carbons show a minor influence. Unfortunately, carbon additives generally lead to an accelerated capacity loss during cycling and an enhanced formation of solid electrolyte decompn. products. The latter was studied in more detail using cyclic voltammetry, XPS, and cycling expts. The results show that carbon additives with a small surface area and a fiber-like morphol. result in the lowest degree of decompn. To completely overcome electrolyte degrdn. caused by the use of carbon additives, a protection concept is developed. A thin alumina coating with a few nanometers thickness was deposited on the carbon fibers by at. layer deposition, which successfully prevents decompn. reactions, reduces long-term capacity fading, and leads to an enhanced overall all-solid-state battery performance.

          Interfacial Processes and Influence of Composite Cathode Microstructure Controlling the Performance of All-Solid-State Lithium Batteries
          Zhang, Wenbo; Weber, Dominik A.; Weigand, Harald; Arlt, Tobias; Manke, Ingo; Schroeder, Daniel; Koerver, Raimund; Leichtweiss, Thomas; Hartmann, Pascal; Zeier, Wolfgang G.; Janek, Juergen
          ACS Applied Materials & Interfaces (2017), 9 (21), 17835-17845CODEN: AAMICK; ISSN:1944-8244. (American Chemical Society)
          All-solid-state lithium-ion batteries have the potential to become an important class of next-generation electrochem. energy storage devices. However, for achieving competitive performance, a better understanding of the interfacial processes at the electrodes is necessary for optimized electrode compns. to be developed. In this work, the interfacial processes between the solid electrolyte (Li10GeP2S12) and the electrode materials (In/InLi and LixCoO2) are monitored using impedance spectroscopy and galvanostatic cycling, showing a large resistance contribution and kinetic hindrance at the metal anode. The effect of different fractions of the solid electrolyte in the composite cathodes on the rate performance is tested. The results demonstrate the necessity of a carefully designed composite microstructure depending on the desired applications of an all-solid-state battery. While a relatively low mass fraction of solid electrolyte is sufficient for high energy d., a higher fraction of solid electrolyte is required for high power d.
